<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8"/>
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"/>
<title>User Personas — Next Loyalty Programme</title>
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=DM+Sans:wght@400;500;600;700;800&family=Inter:wght@300;400;500;600&display=swap" rel="stylesheet"/>
<style>
*,*::before,*::after{box-sizing:border-box;margin:0;padding:0}
:root{
  --navy:#0d1f3c;--navy-mid:#1a2e50;--navy-light:#2a4070;
  --border:#dde4f0;--bg:#f0f4f9;--bg-white:#ffffff;
  --text-dark:#0f172a;--text-mid:#334155;--text-soft:#64748b;
  --text-white:#ffffff;--text-muted:rgba(255,255,255,0.6);
  --indigo:#6c8eea;--gold:#f59e0b;--green:#16a34a;--red:#dc2626;--blue:#2563eb;--purple:#7c3aed;
  --font-head:'DM Sans',sans-serif;--font-body:'Inter',sans-serif;
}
body{font-family:var(--font-body);background:var(--bg);color:var(--text-dark);min-height:100vh;-webkit-font-smoothing:antialiased;}

/* NAV */
.top-bar{background:var(--navy);padding:16px 40px;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:space-between;}
.brand{display:flex;align-items:center;gap:10px;}
.brand-tag{font-size:9px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:2px;text-transform:uppercase;background:rgba(108,142,234,0.2);color:var(--indigo);border:1px solid rgba(108,142,234,0.3);padding:3px 10px;border-radius:4px;}
.brand-name{font-family:var(--font-head);font-size:16px;font-weight:700;color:#fff;}
.scroll-nav{display:flex;gap:8px;align-items:center;}
.nav-dot{width:8px;height:8px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(255,255,255,0.25);cursor:pointer;transition:background 0.2s;}
.nav-dot.active{background:var(--indigo);}
.nav-label{font-size:10px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.4);margin-left:4px;}

/* PAGE */
.page{max-width:1080px;margin:0 auto;padding:40px 40px 80px;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:40px;}

/* PERSONA CARD */
.persona-card{background:var(--bg-white);border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:14px;overflow:hidden;box-shadow:0 2px 12px rgba(0,0,0,0.07);}
.persona-layout{display:grid;grid-template-columns:260px 1fr;}

/* LEFT PANEL */
.left-panel{background:var(--navy);padding:32px 24px;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:20px;}
.persona-avatar{width:64px;height:64px;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-family:var(--font-head);font-size:26px;font-weight:800;color:#fff;margin-bottom:4px;}
.av-customer{background:linear-gradient(135deg,#6c8eea,#3b5fd9);}
.av-credit{background:linear-gradient(135deg,#7c3aed,#4f1dab);}
.av-associate{background:linear-gradient(135deg,#059669,#065f46);}
.persona-name{font-family:var(--font-head);font-size:22px;font-weight:800;color:#fff;line-height:1.1;}
.persona-role{font-size:11px;font-weight:600;color:var(--indigo);letter-spacing:0.5px;margin-top:2px;}
.context-snapshot{font-size:11.5px;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.7);line-height:1.7;border-top:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.12);padding-top:16px;}
.context-label{font-size:9px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:2px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--indigo);margin-bottom:8px;}
.meta-row{display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:8px;border-top:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.12);padding-top:16px;}
.meta-item{display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:2px;}
.meta-key{font-size:8px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1.5px;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.35);}
.meta-val{font-size:11px;font-weight:600;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.85);}
.type-badge{display:inline-block;font-size:9px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:1px;text-transform:uppercase;padding:3px 10px;border-radius:10px;}
.badge-primary{background:rgba(34,197,94,0.2);color:#86efac;border:1px solid rgba(34,197,94,0.3);}
.badge-secondary{background:rgba(124,58,237,0.2);color:#c4b5fd;border:1px solid rgba(124,58,237,0.3);}
.badge-internal{background:rgba(245,158,11,0.15);color:#fcd34d;border:1px solid rgba(245,158,11,0.3);}

/* RIGHT PANEL */
.right-panel{padding:28px 32px;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:22px;}
.section-label{font-size:9px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:2px;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:10px;}
.label-gold{color:var(--gold);}
.label-green{color:var(--green);}
.label-red{color:var(--red);}
.label-blue{color:var(--blue);}
.label-purple{color:var(--purple);}

/* Bars */
.bar-list{display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:7px;}
.bar-item{display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:10px;}
.bar-accent{width:3px;min-height:18px;border-radius:2px;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:3px;}
.bar-gold{background:var(--gold);}
.bar-red{background:var(--red);}
.bar-blue{background:var(--blue);}
.bar-purple{background:var(--purple);}
.bar-text{font-size:12px;color:var(--text-mid);line-height:1.65;}

/* Goals pills */
.pills{display:flex;flex-wrap:wrap;gap:7px;}
.pill{font-size:11px;font-weight:500;color:#166534;background:#dcfce7;border:1px solid #bbf7d0;border-radius:20px;padding:4px 12px;line-height:1.4;}

/* Fears */
.fears-list{display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:6px;}
.fear-item{display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:8px;font-size:12px;color:var(--text-mid);line-height:1.6;}
.fear-dot{width:5px;height:5px;border-radius:50%;background:var(--red);flex-shrink:0;margin-top:6px;}

/* Two col */
.two-col{display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:20px;}

/* Divider */
.h-div{height:1px;background:var(--border);}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="top-bar">
  <div class="brand">
    <span class="brand-tag">User Personas</span>
    <span class="brand-name">Next Loyalty Programme</span>
  </div>
  <nav class="scroll-nav">
    <div class="nav-dot active"></div>
    <div class="nav-dot"></div>
    <div class="nav-dot"></div>
    <span class="nav-label">3 Personas</span>
  </nav>
</div>

<div class="page">

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
       PERSONA 1 — CUSTOMER (CASH/DEBIT)
  ══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="persona-card" id="persona-1">
    <div class="persona-layout">

      <div class="left-panel">
        <div>
          <div class="persona-avatar av-customer">C</div>
          <div class="persona-name">Clara</div>
          <div class="persona-role">Customer — Cash / Debit Shopper</div>
        </div>

        <div>
          <div class="context-label">Context Snapshot</div>
          <div class="context-snapshot">A habitual, high-frequency shopper who has built Next into her routine over many years without any digital loyalty relationship. Shops across channels — browsing on her phone, purchasing online, and visiting stores regularly — but manages each channel separately because the systems don't connect them. Highly organised around returns: plans buys expecting to return some items, and is anxious about any system that might penalise that. Engages actively with loyalty programmes at other retailers (Boots, M&S Sparks) and uses them strategically — choosing where to shop based on where she'll earn. Expects immediate earn transparency at checkout and will not trust a programme whose balance she cannot verify in real time.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="meta-row">
          <div class="meta-item"><div class="meta-key">Type</div><div class="meta-val"><span class="type-badge badge-primary">Primary User</span></div></div>
          <div class="meta-item"><div class="meta-key">Industry / Domain</div><div class="meta-val">Fashion &amp; Home Retail</div></div>
          <div class="meta-item"><div class="meta-key">Tech Comfort</div><div class="meta-val">Moderate — app-capable but selective</div></div>
          <div class="meta-item"><div class="meta-key">Primary Device</div><div class="meta-val">Smartphone + laptop</div></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="right-panel">

        <div>
          <div class="section-label label-gold">Responsibilities &amp; Their World</div>
          <div class="bar-list">
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-gold"></div><div class="bar-text">Shops across online, app, and in-store channels for clothing, footwear, and home products — often starting browsing in one channel and completing the purchase in another</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-gold"></div><div class="bar-text">Manages her own purchase and returns lifecycle — orders multiples expecting to return some, monitors return windows, and tracks refund status independently</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-gold"></div><div class="bar-text">Actively tracks loyalty balances across multiple programmes (Boots Advantage Card, M&amp;S Sparks, Tesco Clubcard) and routes spend decisions accordingly</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-gold"></div><div class="bar-text">Manages household and family purchasing alongside personal fashion spend — driving higher basket value and multi-category need across homeware and clothing</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-gold"></div><div class="bar-text">Evaluates seasonal sale events in advance — plans what she wants, monitors timing, and expects access to be worth the wait</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="h-div"></div>

        <div class="two-col">
          <div>
            <div class="section-label label-green">Goals &amp; Motivations</div>
            <div class="pills">
              <span class="pill">Earn recognition for multi-year spend without taking out a credit account</span>
              <span class="pill">See her points balance grow visibly after every purchase</span>
              <span class="pill">Access Next sale early — as a loyalty reward, not a credit product</span>
              <span class="pill">Receive personalised offers relevant to what she actually buys — not generic emails</span>
              <span class="pill">Use loyalty across channels seamlessly with one scan or card</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="section-label label-red">Pains &amp; Frustrations</div>
            <div class="bar-list">
              <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-red"></div><div class="bar-text">Feels invisible as a long-tenure customer because Next has no mechanism to recognise 15+ years of spend, leading to a purely transactional relationship with no sense of being known</div></div>
              <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-red"></div><div class="bar-text">Gets locked out of VIP Sale early access because she uses a debit card rather than a credit account, even though her spend pattern qualifies as loyal behaviour</div></div>
              <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-red"></div><div class="bar-text">Finds it anxious-making that Next's systems might penalise returns, resulting in reluctance to engage with any new data-collecting programme without a clear statement of how her data will be used</div></div>
              <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-red"></div><div class="bar-text">Dislikes loyalty programmes with complex earn mechanics because she cannot quickly evaluate what she gets, leading to lapse when the mental effort of tracking outweighs the perceived reward</div></div>
              <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-red"></div><div class="bar-text">Feels frustrated that her nextpay account and online shopping account are separate systems she discovered were unlinked only during a failed in-store return, affecting her trust in Next's data infrastructure</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="h-div"></div>

        <div>
          <div class="section-label label-blue">Behaviours / Decisioning Context</div>
          <div class="bar-list">
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-blue"></div><div class="bar-text">Routes spend toward retailers with active loyalty balances — walks past Superdrug to reach Boots specifically for Advantage Card points; applies the same logic when choosing between Next and a competitor</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-blue"></div><div class="bar-text">Reads earn mechanics before committing to a programme — Boots ("spend £1, get 4 points, 4 points = 1p") earns her trust; programmes she cannot summarise in one sentence get abandoned</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-blue"></div><div class="bar-text">Uses the in-store scan only if it is reachable within 4 seconds of opening the app and confirms with a visible on-screen response — otherwise abandons it to avoid holding up the queue</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-blue"></div><div class="bar-text">Evaluates in-store recognition by whether the associate acknowledges she has points, not whether they greet her by name — values the functional signal over the performative gesture</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="h-div"></div>

        <div>
          <div class="section-label label-red">Fears &amp; Concerns</div>
          <div class="fears-list">
            <div class="fear-item"><div class="fear-dot"></div><div>That signing up for the loyalty programme will give Next licence to use her returns behaviour against her — the programme feels like surveillance if it tracks returns data alongside purchase data</div></div>
            <div class="fear-item"><div class="fear-dot"></div><div>That the app-only loyalty experience will eventually exclude older customers in her network — she advocates for a card fallback and would disengage from a programme that abandons less digital-confident users</div></div>
            <div class="fear-item"><div class="fear-dot"></div><div>That the early access benefit will still require a credit account even after the loyalty programme launches — making the headline benefit inaccessible to cash customers again</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="h-div"></div>

        <div>
          <div class="section-label label-purple">Tools Relied On</div>
          <div class="bar-list">
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-purple"></div><div class="bar-text">Loyalty apps — primary engagement channel for points tracking and in-store scan; Boots app, M&amp;S Sparks, Costa app</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-purple"></div><div class="bar-text">Retail websites and apps — online browsing, purchase, and order management; next.co.uk, ASOS, Dunelm</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-purple"></div><div class="bar-text">Email — primary channel for sale notifications, order confirmation, and returns receipts; critical for order lookup at till</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-purple"></div><div class="bar-text">In-store — touchpoints for trying on, Click &amp; Collect collection, and impulse add-ons; physical store visit often triggers unplanned purchases</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-purple"></div><div class="bar-text">Social media — discovery channel for new products and sale awareness; often the first touchpoint in a multi-channel purchase journey</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
       PERSONA 2 — CUSTOMER (NEXTPAY)
  ══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="persona-card" id="persona-2">
    <div class="persona-layout">

      <div class="left-panel">
        <div>
          <div class="persona-avatar av-credit">N</div>
          <div class="persona-name">Nathan</div>
          <div class="persona-role">Customer — nextpay Account Holder</div>
        </div>

        <div>
          <div class="context-label">Context Snapshot</div>
          <div class="context-snapshot">A high-frequency, multi-category Next shopper who holds a nextpay credit account and already benefits from VIP Sale early access — the only loyalty signal Next currently provides. Shops primarily online and via the app, with in-store visits for considered purchases. Treats the credit account as a payment tool, not a loyalty reward, and experiences tension when the two are conflated. Engages actively with the loyalty benefit he receives (early access) but is aware it is credit-gated and feels the distinction is important. Motivated by visible progress and experiential rewards — converts Tesco points to restaurant deals rather than cash-off vouchers. Would engage deeply with a Next loyalty programme that is built on top of the credit relationship rather than replacing it, but is alert to the loyalty programme becoming a vehicle for financial upselling.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="meta-row">
          <div class="meta-item"><div class="meta-key">Type</div><div class="meta-val"><span class="type-badge badge-secondary">Primary User</span></div></div>
          <div class="meta-item"><div class="meta-key">Industry / Domain</div><div class="meta-val">Fashion &amp; Home Retail</div></div>
          <div class="meta-item"><div class="meta-key">Tech Comfort</div><div class="meta-val">High — online-first shopper</div></div>
          <div class="meta-item"><div class="meta-key">Primary Device</div><div class="meta-val">Smartphone (primary) + laptop</div></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="right-panel">

        <div>
          <div class="section-label label-gold">Responsibilities &amp; Their World</div>
          <div class="bar-list">
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-gold"></div><div class="bar-text">Shops across clothing, footwear, and home — uses nextpay for large purchases to spread payment; prefers to manage account online and reviews statements regularly</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-gold"></div><div class="bar-text">Plans seasonal sale participation in advance — books diary reminders for VIP Sale windows, prepares a wishlist, and acts within the early access slot knowing best items sell out quickly</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-gold"></div><div class="bar-text">Manages multiple loyalty programmes actively — evaluates each one by how the rewards feel when redeemed, not just the accumulation rate; prioritises experiential redemptions over cash-off vouchers</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-gold"></div><div class="bar-text">Shops online-first with occasional in-store visits for considered purchases such as furniture, outerwear, or items where seeing the product matters; uses Click &amp; Collect for convenience</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-gold"></div><div class="bar-text">Advocates naturally for Next among people in his network — has a long-standing positive relationship with the brand despite frustrations with the absence of a formal loyalty programme</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="h-div"></div>

        <div class="two-col">
          <div>
            <div class="section-label label-green">Goals &amp; Motivations</div>
            <div class="pills">
              <span class="pill">Earn points across every purchase — not just those made on credit</span>
              <span class="pill">Access experiential rewards that feel meaningful — not just pence off</span>
              <span class="pill">See visible progress toward the next meaningful milestone</span>
              <span class="pill">Keep loyalty clearly separate from his credit relationship</span>
              <span class="pill">Use the Next app as a unified hub for both loyalty and account management</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="section-label label-red">Pains &amp; Frustrations</div>
            <div class="bar-list">
              <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-red"></div><div class="bar-text">Feels that VIP Sale access is framed as a credit benefit rather than a loyalty reward, resulting in a sense that his early access is contingent on a financial product rather than on his behaviour as a shopper</div></div>
              <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-red"></div><div class="bar-text">Gets no recognition for in-store purchases made on his debit card rather than nextpay, meaning the majority of his basket spend generates no loyalty signal at all</div></div>
              <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-red"></div><div class="bar-text">Finds the lack of visible points accumulation frustrating because he cannot track whether the relationship with Next is building toward anything — the balance is invisible because it doesn't exist</div></div>
              <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-red"></div><div class="bar-text">Dislikes programmes that change their terms without plain-English explanation — lapsed from John Lewis specifically because a programme change communication was written in corporate language he couldn't parse</div></div>
              <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-red"></div><div class="bar-text">Feels anxious that a Next loyalty programme might use his account data to push credit products or increase his nextpay limit — wants the loyalty relationship kept completely separate from the financial relationship</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="h-div"></div>

        <div>
          <div class="section-label label-blue">Behaviours / Decisioning Context</div>
          <div class="bar-list">
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-blue"></div><div class="bar-text">Chooses retailers that upgrade his experience — went to a nicer restaurant than he'd normally choose because Tesco points converted to a restaurant meal deal; the reward elevated the decision, not just the price</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-blue"></div><div class="bar-text">Disengages immediately when programme mechanics are unclear — "if I have to read a document to understand a loyalty scheme, I'm out"; will not invest effort in a programme he cannot evaluate in 30 seconds</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-blue"></div><div class="bar-text">Spends more when a reward is in play — M&amp;S credit made him choose a better coat than planned; the reward functions as permission to upgrade the decision, not just a discount on the original one</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="h-div"></div>

        <div>
          <div class="section-label label-red">Fears &amp; Concerns</div>
          <div class="fears-list">
            <div class="fear-item"><div class="fear-dot"></div><div>That the loyalty programme will become a back-channel for financial product upselling — using loyalty data to identify customers for credit limit increases or new nextpay promotions</div></div>
            <div class="fear-item"><div class="fear-dot"></div><div>That programme terms will change after he has accumulated a significant balance — the John Lewis experience made him cautious about investing engagement in a programme that could be restructured without fair notice</div></div>
            <div class="fear-item"><div class="fear-dot"></div><div>That his returns history will be surfaced through the loyalty system and used to restrict his account — the same anxiety as cash customers, amplified by the fact he already holds an active credit account that can be restricted</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="h-div"></div>

        <div>
          <div class="section-label label-purple">Tools Relied On</div>
          <div class="bar-list">
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-purple"></div><div class="bar-text">Next app and website — primary shopping and account management channels; uses for browsing, purchasing, order tracking, and nextpay account review</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-purple"></div><div class="bar-text">Loyalty apps — Tesco Clubcard (experiential redemptions), Pret a Manger (daily use, in-store scan benchmark); evaluates all loyalty apps by their in-store scan speed</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-purple"></div><div class="bar-text">Email — receives VIP Sale notification here; the most valued Next communication he receives; expects the loyalty programme to use this channel for milestone and access notifications</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-purple"></div><div class="bar-text">In-store — visits for considered purchases; expects the in-store experience to reflect his loyalty status even though current POS cannot surface it</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-purple"></div><div class="bar-text">Push notifications — tolerates for genuinely relevant alerts (sale access windows, points milestones); dismisses generic promotional push</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
       PERSONA 3 — STORE ASSOCIATE
  ══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="persona-card" id="persona-3">
    <div class="persona-layout">

      <div class="left-panel">
        <div>
          <div class="persona-avatar av-associate">S</div>
          <div class="persona-name">Sana</div>
          <div class="persona-role">Store Associate</div>
        </div>

        <div>
          <div class="context-label">Context Snapshot</div>
          <div class="context-snapshot">A customer-centric, full-time store associate who spends approximately half her shift at or near the till and the other half on the shop floor. Intrinsically motivated to deliver differentiated service to regulars — has built informal recognition relationships with a small set of customers through personal memory alone, which is non-scalable and shift-dependent. Highly attuned to queue dynamics: knows exactly how much time she has with each customer and feels the pressure of complex transactions building a queue behind her. Frustrated by system limitations rather than by the work itself. Has specific, bounded knowledge needs — wants to know whether a customer is loyal and whether they've had recent problems, but does not want their name or purchase detail. Identifies the loyalty programme rollout as a service upgrade she genuinely wants to deliver, if the training is practical enough for her to feel confident at the till from day one.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="meta-row">
          <div class="meta-item"><div class="meta-key">Type</div><div class="meta-val"><span class="type-badge badge-internal">Internal User</span></div></div>
          <div class="meta-item"><div class="meta-key">Industry / Domain</div><div class="meta-val">Fashion Retail — In-Store Operations</div></div>
          <div class="meta-item"><div class="meta-key">Tech Comfort</div><div class="meta-val">Moderate — POS-native, handheld-capable</div></div>
          <div class="meta-item"><div class="meta-key">Primary Device</div><div class="meta-val">Touchscreen POS till + shared handheld</div></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="right-panel">

        <div>
          <div class="section-label label-gold">Responsibilities &amp; Their World</div>
          <div class="bar-list">
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-gold"></div><div class="bar-text">Processes purchases, returns, and Click &amp; Collect collections at the POS till — currently sees only items, price, and payment method; no customer identity data is surfaced during standard transactions</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-gold"></div><div class="bar-text">Manages customer queries on the shop floor — stock availability, sizing, promotions, Click &amp; Collect status — using handheld devices shared across the team (approximately 4 per floor)</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-gold"></div><div class="bar-text">Handles complex return situations involving multi-email identity fragmentation — spends up to 12 minutes searching for orders across multiple email addresses while managing the live queue</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-gold"></div><div class="bar-text">Introduces new programmes and promotions to customers at the till — currently limited by rigid scripting and no customer context, which makes the introduction feel forced and poorly targeted</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-gold"></div><div class="bar-text">Maintains informal recognition of a small set of regulars through personal memory — builds warmth into those interactions but loses it entirely when off-shift, making it non-scalable</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="h-div"></div>

        <div class="two-col">
          <div>
            <div class="section-label label-green">Goals &amp; Motivations</div>
            <div class="pills">
              <span class="pill">Know whether a customer is loyal — without needing to recognise their face</span>
              <span class="pill">Resolve returns in under 2 minutes using a reliable customer identifier</span>
              <span class="pill">Lead with empathy in difficult interactions rather than being forced into reactive mode</span>
              <span class="pill">Introduce the loyalty programme confidently from day one of launch</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="section-label label-red">Pains &amp; Frustrations</div>
            <div class="bar-list">
              <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-red"></div><div class="bar-text">Finds it impossible to differentiate service for loyal customers because the till system gives her zero customer identity — forcing her to treat a 10-year regular the same as a first-time visitor</div></div>
              <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-red"></div><div class="bar-text">Gets stuck in extended return searches due to multi-email identity fragmentation, resulting in queue build-up, customer exasperation, and pressure to cut corners on verification</div></div>
              <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-red"></div><div class="bar-text">Feels forced into reactive empathy in complaint interactions because she has no visibility of recent service issues — cannot lead with "I know you've had a difficult experience" without the system telling her so</div></div>
              <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-red"></div><div class="bar-text">Dislikes rigid promotion scripting because it produces awkward interactions when the offer is contextually irrelevant to the customer — describing the experience of promoting Click &amp; Collect to customers already walking away</div></div>
              <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-red"></div><div class="bar-text">Feels that current in-store technology does not reflect her actual capability — she is a capable and motivated service provider working around system limitations that are not her fault</div></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="h-div"></div>

        <div>
          <div class="section-label label-blue">Behaviours / Decisioning Context</div>
          <div class="bar-list">
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-blue"></div><div class="bar-text">Prioritises queue speed over thoroughness under pressure — will process a return without fully checking everything when a queue is building, accepting service risk to manage social pressure</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-blue"></div><div class="bar-text">Hesitates at the till when uncertain about programme mechanics — treats any moment of hesitation as a loss of customer confidence that is hard to recover from; will only promote something she can explain in one sentence</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-blue"></div><div class="bar-text">Learns best through short roleplay at the start of a shift rather than e-learning or video — knowledge that is not practised verbally before a shift is typically forgotten within a week</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="h-div"></div>

        <div>
          <div class="section-label label-red">Fears &amp; Concerns</div>
          <div class="fears-list">
            <div class="fear-item"><div class="fear-dot"></div><div>That the POS loyalty display will surface data that causes her to treat customers worse — specifically returns frequency — and that a loyalty indicator will become a reason for suspicion rather than a prompt for better service</div></div>
            <div class="fear-item"><div class="fear-dot"></div><div>That the loyalty programme will be launched without adequate till-side training, putting her in the position of introducing something she cannot explain confidently — replicating the Click &amp; Collect rollout failure</div></div>
            <div class="fear-item"><div class="fear-dot"></div><div>That customers who cannot use the app will be excluded from earning in-store, creating a two-tier experience at the till that she will have to manage and explain</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="h-div"></div>

        <div>
          <div class="section-label label-purple">Tools Relied On</div>
          <div class="bar-list">
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-purple"></div><div class="bar-text">POS touchscreen till — primary work tool; handles payment, returns, and nextpay; currently surfaces no customer identity or loyalty data</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-purple"></div><div class="bar-text">Shared handheld devices — stock checking, Click &amp; Collect confirmation, and barcode scanning on the shop floor; limited availability (4 shared across the floor)</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-purple"></div><div class="bar-text">Returns lookup system — email and order number search; current failure mode when customers have multiple registered emails or no order confirmation accessible</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-purple"></div><div class="bar-text">Personal memory — current primary mechanism for recognising regulars and recalling their preferences; works only for her personally, on her shifts, for a small number of customers</div></div>
            <div class="bar-item"><div class="bar-accent bar-purple"></div><div class="bar-text">Till-side reference materials — cheat sheets for promotions; expects the same format for loyalty programme launch to serve as a quick-reference during live transactions</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

</div>
</body>
</html>
